`getBook`, `categoryOf`, and `searchBooks`' inner category lookup all do `Array.find`/`filter` over the full `books`/`categories` arrays, and are called repeatedly per render and per search keystroke.

- `src/lib/content.ts:61-71` — `getBook`, `booksInCategory`, `categoryOf`
- `src/lib/content.ts:180` — `categoryOf(b)` called inside `searchBooks`'s `.map()`, so every keystroke does an O(books × categories) scan

```ts
// content.ts — replace linear scans with Maps built once at module load
const bookById = new Map(books.map((b) => [b.id, b]))
const categoryById = new Map(categories.map((c) => [c.id, c]))
const booksByCategory = new Map<string, Book[]>()
for (const b of books) {
  const list = booksByCategory.get(b.categoryId) ?? []
  list.push(b)
  booksByCategory.set(b.categoryId, list)
}

export function getBook(id: string | undefined): Book | undefined {
  return id ? bookById.get(id) : undefined
}
export function booksInCategory(categoryId: string): Book[] {
  return booksByCategory.get(categoryId) ?? []
}
export function categoryOf(book: Book): Category | undefined {
  return categoryById.get(book.categoryId)
}
```

Cheap with today's ~4 books, but it's called on every render of `BookMap`/`Reader`/`ContinueStrip` and inside the search hot path — fix now before the catalog grows.

**`bookStats()` recomputed every render, for every card** (`src/lib/content.ts:154-164`, called from `Library.tsx:32`, `BookMap.tsx:75`, and `Library.tsx:111` inside a totals reducer). It's pure over static book data (word counts, reduces over chapters) — a great memoization candidate since `books` never changes after load.

```ts
// content.ts
const statsCache = new Map<string, BookStats>()
export function bookStats(b: Book): BookStats {
  const cached = statsCache.get(b.id)
  if (cached) return cached
  const stats = computeStats(b)   // existing body, renamed
  statsCache.set(b.id, stats)
  return stats
}
```

This directly compounds with fix #2 — once `BookCard` no longer re-renders needlessly, remaining renders still recompute `bookStats` from scratch each time; caching removes that too.

**Chapter parsing has no cache** (`src/lib/content.ts:110-145`, `loadChapter`). Every time a user navigates to a chapter — including re-visiting one they already read — the raw markdown is re-parsed (title regex, section splitting, `mdToHtml`/`marked.parse`) from scratch. `Reader.tsx:35` calls `loadChapter` on every `bookId`/`n` change with no cache layer.

```ts
// content.ts
const chapterCache = new Map<string, Promise<Chapter | null>>()
export function loadChapter(bookId: string, n: number): Promise<Chapter | null> {
  const key = `${bookId}:${n}`
  const cached = chapterCache.get(key)
  if (cached) return cached
  const promise = loadChapterUncached(bookId, n)   // existing body, renamed, still async
  chapterCache.set(key, promise)
  return promise
}
```

**`Markdown` component doesn't memoize its parse** (`src/lib/markdown.tsx:15-21`) — `mdToHtml(text)` runs in the render body on every call, so any parent re-render reparses unchanged markdown. Combine with `React.memo` on `Markdown` (props are just `text`/`className`, easy to shallow-compare) so it only reparses when `text` actually changes.

